"info": "The vSphere content pack provides powerful insight into your vCenter Server and ESXi logs, allowing you to make informed and proactive decisions within your environment. This content pack enables:<br><br>Proactive monitoring of your vSphere environment<br><ul><li>Quickly identify issues:&nbsp;The&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=2&amp;viewId=2\">General - Problems</a>&nbsp;dashboard gives you a single pane of glass to find problems in your vSphere environment while the&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=28&amp;viewId=3\">General - Performance</a>&nbsp;dashboard does the same to isolate performance issues.</li><li>Drill down to determine the root cause:&nbsp;Dashboard filters make it easy to see logs from specific parts of your vSphere environment.</li><li>Easily consume data:&nbsp;Powerful and dynamic visualizations make it possible to detect anomalies, perform trending analysis, and pinpoint specific issues through targeted queries.</li><li>Alerts:&nbsp;Know what to monitor in your vSphere logs and get notified when such events are detected.</li></ul><br>Track changes and isolate security threats<br><ul><li>Configuration management:&nbsp;Track user-initiated changes and automated vSphere actions through the&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=28&amp;viewId=11\">vCenter Server - Tasks</a>&nbsp;dashboard.</li><li>Environmental changes:&nbsp;Get a complete picture from the&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=28&amp;viewId=5\">Security - Auditing</a>&nbsp;dashboard or see more specific information like what VMs are being moved through&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=28&amp;viewId=20\">DRS and HA actions</a>.</li><li>Security:&nbsp;The&nbsp;<a href=\"/\">Security - Authentication</a>&nbsp;dashboard allows you to find who is logging into vSphere devices from which locations and through what means.</li></ul><br>Additional information and context<br><ul><li>Query notes:&nbsp;Each dashboard widget includes information about the widget with links to documentation, knowledge base articles, and any other information making it possible to understand the data presented.</li><li>Inventory:&nbsp;The&nbsp;<a href=\"/home?contextId=com.vmware.vsphere&amp;amp;datePreset=LAST_24_HOURS&amp;amp;viewId=28&amp;viewId=7\">General - Inventory</a>&nbsp;dashboard quantifies results seen through vSphere logs making it simple to ensure complete environment monitoring.</li></ul><br><br>Changelog<br><ul><li>v4.6: Bug fixes</li><ul></ul><li>v4.5: Enhanced security dashboards and, bug fixes</li></ul><ul><li>v4.4: Enhanced security dashboards, new security alerts, new vCenter Server Reconfigurations dashboard, bug fixes</li><li>v4.3: Support for vCenter Server 6.5, new dashboards for vSphere - Monitoring and Replication, bug fixes</li><li>v4.0: Bug fixes. IMPORTANT: This content pack&nbsp;does not support vCenter Server 6.5</li><li>v3.6: Bug fixes. IMPORTANT:&nbsp;Changes to agent groups included, recreating agent groups is recommended!</li></ul>",
"instructions": "In order to harness the power of the vSphere content pack, the following configurations are required:<br><br><b><a href=\"/admin/vsphere\">vSphere Integration</a></b><br><br><ul><li>vCenter Server Events, Tasks, and Alarms: Checkbox should be selected for each vCenter Server instance -- even if instances are in Linked Mode.</li><li>ESXi Syslog: Checkbox should be configured for each vCenter Server instance on which ESXi logs are desired with the checkbox to configure ESXi hosts. Note if ESXi hosts are already configured to forward syslog to Log Insight through a means outside of vSphere integration then the vSphere content pack will still work. To be clear, this means that vSphere integration for ESXi hosts is not a requirement for the vSphere content pack, but collecting syslog from ESXi is required.</li></ul><br><br><b><a href=\"/admin/vrops\">vRealize Operations integration</a></b><br><br>Note none of the checkboxes are required though integration is required.<br><br><b>vCenter Server Application Logs</b><br><br>For vCenter Server 5.5 and 6.0, the Log Insight agent should be installed. For Virtual Appliance instances running vSphere 6.0 the&nbsp;vSphere 6.0 - VCSA (Linux) Essential&nbsp;<a href=\"/admin/agents\">agent group</a>&nbsp;should be enabled and configured. The&nbsp;vSphere 6.0 - VCSA (Linux) Complete&nbsp;<a href=\"/admin/agents\">agent group</a>&nbsp;can be used for more comprehensive vCenter Server application log collection though the vSphere content pack does not leverage these additional log files today. Windows and SSO agent groups are also included. If running vCenter Server 6.5 then vSphere integration is sufficient. You may consider enabling syslog on vCenter Server by:<br><br><ol><li>Configure VAMI: Log into VAMI on port 5480 and configure the syslog section to point to Log Insight over port 514</li><li>Enable vpxd logging: Under Advanced Settings, enable vpxd logging</li></ol><br><br>Be sure to install the applicable operating system content packs in order to have full visibility into all available events:<br><ul><li>ESXi: Linux</li><li>vCenter Server: Microsoft - Windows</li><li>vCenter Server Appliance (VCSA): Linux</li></ul><br>Also, please checkout the other VMware content packs that may be applicable to your Software Defined Data Center in the&nbsp;<a href=\"/contentpack?marketplace=marketplace\">Marketplace</a>&nbsp;including:<br><ul><li>VMware - NSX-vSphere</li></ul>",
